## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 4 Critical · 1 High · 2 Medium · 0 Low**

This suite is dominated by **self-referential / tautological assertions**. Four of eight tests assert `output == input` using inputs specifically chosen so the operation under test is a no-op. These tests can never catch a regression.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Self-referential: `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–42)

`Normalize()` does `Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`. The input `"alice"` is already lowercase and trimmed, so the assertion `input == result` is trivially true. The test would pass even if `Normalize` were `return name;`.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — tautological, input is already normalized
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// ✅ Fix — use input that exercises the transformation
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize("  ALICE ");
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

#### 2. Self-referential: `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 71–77)

Input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase. `.ToUpper()` returns the same string. This test cannot detect a broken `ToUpper` implementation.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — no-op input
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// ✅ Fix — use mixed-case input, assert against literal expected value
var result = "hello".ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

#### 3. Self-referential: `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 55–61)

`GetDisplayName()` returns `Name` verbatim. The assertion `user.Name == display` is `user.Name == user.Name` — asserting a property against itself. The word "Formatted" in the test name implies a transformation that doesn't exist and isn't verified.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — asserts property == same property
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// ✅ Fix — assert against a literal expected value
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);
// If GetDisplayName *should* format (e.g., "Alice (30)"), assert that instead
// and fix the production code.
```

#### 4. Tautological round-trip on lossy mapping: `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 45–53)

`ToDto` **drops** `Id` and `Email`; `ToEntity` **drops** `Age`. A round-trip can never reproduce the original entity. The test asserts `entity.Id == backToEntity.Id` (i.e., `1 == 0`) — this either **silently fails** or the test was never actually run. The round-trip approach is fundamentally wrong for a lossy mapping.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — round-trip on a lossy pair of mappers
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Id, backToEntity.Id);       // 1 != 0
Assert.AreEqual(entity.FullName, backToEntity.FullName); // happens to survive
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Email, backToEntity.Email);  // "a@b.com" != ""

// ✅ Fix — test each mapping direction independently
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age); // Age is not mapped — document that
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);    // Id is not mapped
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email); // Email is not mapped
}
```

---

### 🟠 High

#### 5. Missing negative-path tests: `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 63–69)

The happy-path assertion (`input == result`) is correct here — `ValidateEmail` is documented to return its input when valid. But there are **zero tests** for the throwing path. Invalid-email behavior is completely unverified.

```csharp
// ✅ Add — verify the guard clause works
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_MissingAtSign_ThrowsArgumentException()
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail("not-an-email"));
}
```

---

### 🟡 Medium

| # | Test | Issue | Fix |
|---|------|-------|-----|
| 6 | `Clone_ProducesEqualObject` (line 27–34) | Verifies value equality but **never asserts the clone is a different instance**. Test would pass if `Clone()` returned `this`. | Add `Assert.AreNotSame(original, clone);` |
| 7 | `Serialize_ThenDeserialize_ProducesOriginal` (line 9–16) | Legitimate round-trip (JSON serialization is non-lossy), but asserts individual properties instead of the whole object. If a new property is added to `UserDto`, the test stays green without covering it. | Consider overriding `Equals`/adding a record, or explicitly enumerating all properties with a comment to update when the DTO changes. |

---

